observations.recommendation:
Appropriately record reversion of obligation caused by stale checks to appropriate liability account instead of lodging it to Other Payables;

Verify the validity of payables aged two years and more and send confirmation letters for balances with identified claimants or creditors. Valid claims shall be paid following the rules and regulations provided in Section 59 of the Manual on New Government Accounting System. Otherwise, cause the reversion of the payables to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund;

Maintain separate FS for each economic enterprise; and 

Effect the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify other accounts erroneously booked Other Payables account to ensure that accounts are accurately presented in the financial statements and furnish the Office of the Auditor with a copy of the journal entry voucher.

Propose to the Local Sangguniang to recognize income-generating programs and ventures as Economic Enterprise thru enactment of an ordinance; and

Require the Municipal Treasurer to send written notices to the payee of the existence of the check one month before it becomes stale. For checks that became stale in the hands of the payee and needs replacement, require submission of the said stale checks prior to issuance of new check.

Through the Municipal Treasurer provide the Municipal Accountant with a Certified List of Market and KTC Stallholders and Delinquent Stallholders as of December 31, 2023 with the amount due to facilitate the recording of accrued rental income, and submit thereafter a Monthly Report of Collection and Balances of each stallholder.

Ensure that all stall occupants are covered by the Contract of Lease based on the rental rates fixed under the Municipal Ordinance 65, s-2015, also known as “Revised Local Revenue Code of the Municipality of Kapatagan, Lanao del Norte”; 

Prepare and maintain Report of Payment and Balances for each Stallholders, and periodically reconcile the same with the Reports maintained by the Treasury and Accounting Office; 

Regularly send Billing Statements or Demand Letters to delinquent stallholders to enforce payments; and

Strictly implement the provisions embodied in the contract and Municipal Ordinance 67, s-2015.

The Municipal Accountant 

Recognize the total unpaid rentals in the books of the Municipality to the appropriate receivable and income account, and every year thereafter, record the receivable account based on the Certified List of Stallholders with the duly approved Contract of Lease in compliance with the provision of IPSAS 13; 

Provide subsidiary ledgers for each stallholder and record the corresponding receivable and income therefrom; and

Maintain a complete file of the approved Contract of Lease.

It is further recommended to management that a copy of the contracts be submitted to COA for auditorial review and evaluation within 5 days from execution pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-01 dated February 12, 2009.

Local Development Council to specify the projects, programs and activities chargeable to 20% Development Fund, and stop the practice of lump sum budgeting and inclusion of generic PPAs in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget;

Municipal Budget Officer 

Secure resolution from the Local Sangguniang before affixing signature in the Obligation Request for charges that are stated in generic terms;

Observe proper expenditure classification of the PPAs in the preparation of the Annual Budget;

Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) 

Coordinate with the end user and other concerned offices to ensure that the procurement activities of the PPAs charged to 20% Development Fund are well planned as required in DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1 dated November 4, 2020;

Assess the resources and facilities of the Municipality to evaluate full compliance with the requirements and conditions of the guidelines for projects by administration as provided in Appendix 1 of RA 9184;

Municipal Accountant to observe proper recording of transactions and make necessary journal entry/ies to reclassify the Infrastructure Projects and Fund Transfer to NGOs/POs to appropriate accounts; and

Recipient NGOs/POs to liquidate the said Fund Transfer and ensure compliance with documentary requirements specified in COA Circular 2012-001.

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Voucher to book the unreported assets upon establishment of the initial carrying value and recognize depreciation thereof;

Require the GSO to record the donated properties in the Property Card and to issue Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) to the end-user to enforce accountability of the agency assets; and

Establish policy and procedures with a clearly defined responsibility for the proper receipt, recording, and reporting of donated properties.

Require the officials and employees with unliquidated balances as of year-end to immediately settle the cash advances by sending final demand letters to all concerned personnel;

Withhold the salary of local officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances as authorized under COA Circular 97-002;

Stop the granting of additional cash advances to officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances; and

Submit the documents required in COA Circular 2016-005 to facilitate the write-off of long overdue and outstanding cash advances.

Require the Accounting Office to record the regular purchases of office supplies, drugs, medicines and other supplies/materials as inventory, recognize the corresponding expenses for actual issuances, and maintain stock ledger cards; 
Require the GSO to take control and custody of the supplies held for consumption/distribution, follow the procedures in the requisition and issuance of inventory items, and maintain stock cards;
Require the GSO and the Accounting Office to conduct periodic reconciliation of records to detect discrepancies and effect immediate corrections; and
Provide storage/stockroom with adequate space to accommodate and safeguard all office supplies before consumption or issuance.

We have recommended to the Municipal Municipal  the following:
Ensure the conduct of a complete and accurate physical count of all PPE assets and ensure proper classification and documentation;
Ensure that a representative from the Commission on Audit (COA) is present during future physical inventory counts to provide proper validation and oversight.
Ensure that a Deed of Donation or Property Transfer Receipt is properly executed with the recipient agency before delivering or donating properties to ensure the valid transfer of ownership;
The Municipal Accountant:
To derecognize the cost and corresponding accumulated depreciation of properties that have already been donated to other agencies;
To update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE).
The General Services Officer:
Maintain the Property Cards for PPEs and incorporate the balances in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
Ensure all equipment/property is assigned with Inventory Tags/Stickers. The property sticker shall contain all vital information of each property/equipment for easy identification such as a brief description of the property/equipment, model number, serial number, property number, acquisition date, and to whom assigned/responsible Officer/Employee;
The Inventory Committee:
Prepare annual Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property (RPCSP) for Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) items with a cost below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000;
Conduct a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts following the guidelines and procedures on inventory taking, recognition of those found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability; and
To identify unserviceable properties and prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP)
Initiate the disposal of unserviceable PPEs once they meet the conditions for disposal as outlined in Item B of Part II of the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties under COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1, dated January 30, 2024. Systematic and timely disposal proceedings are essential to avoid further deterioration of the properties and consequent depreciation in their value.

We have recommended to the management to:
Require the Inventory Custodian of the RHU to furnish copies of all PTRs for the items received from the DOH and PHO, as well as the recent report on the physical count of drugs, medicines, medical supplies, and equipment, to the GSO and Municipal Accountant.
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a Journal Entry Voucher to record the unreported assets based on the submitted PTRs and reports from the Inventory Custodian;
Direct the GSO to:
Issue a Property Acknowledgment Receipt (PAR) for properties and equipment received, ensuring that the end-user is held accountable for the assets in their custody;
Coordinate with the Inventory Custodian of RHU in conducting a semi-annual physical count of inventories;
Ensure that the Report of Physical Count of Inventories for drugs, medicines and medical supplies includes those LGU-procured and those received from non-government/government agencies;
Require the GSO, RHU, and Municipal Accountant to establish policies and procedures with clearly defined responsibilities for inventory-taking, reporting, supervision, and disposition of the transferred drugs, medicines, medical supplies, and equipment from the DOH and PHO.

We recommend to the Municipal Vice-Mayor and Members of the SB to:
Stop the granting of financial assistance to its constituents as it is not among its mandated powers, duties and functions under Sections 445 and 447 of RA No. 7160;
Transfer the appropriation of Financial Assistance and Donations under the Office of the Vice Mayor and Sangguniang Bayan to the Executive Branch to properly and effectively utilize such funds for the general welfare of its constituents; 
Concentrate on the legislative functions and strictly confine their programs/projects/activities within the limits of their mandated powers, duties and functions.

The Municipal Treasurer to ensure that its personnel diligently request acknowledgment in the check register from the payee before releasing the checks, and to prepare a schedule of all unreleased checks at year-end for submission to the Municipal Accountant; 

The Municipal Accountant to discontinue the practice of categorizing unreleased checks as outstanding checks in preparing its Bank Reconciliation Statements, avoid assumptions and record the transaction/event as it happened; and 

The Muncipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Voucher per fund at year-end for the restoration of the unreleased checks. The accounting entry for the restoration of the unreleased check shall be a debit to “Cash in Bank, Local Currency Current” account with credit to the appropriate liability account.

Ensure that vacancies on the regular plantilla position of the Municipality are published in accordance with provisions of RA 10741, “An Act Requiring Regular Publication of Existing Vacant Positions in Government Office, Appropriating Funds therefore, and for Other Purposes”;

Prioritize and consider filling up the vacant positions by hiring new employees or expediting the promotion of deserving employees to enhance its services to attain full implementation of programs, plans and activities of the Municipality for the optimal benefit of the constituents as well as to provide equal job opportunities to the community; and

   Give priority to the existing Job Order workers in the appointment to the vacant positions provided that such workers meet the appropriate eligibility and other qualification requirements for the position subject to existing Civil Service law and rules.

